<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>When the Fed engages in expansionary monetary policy, what happens to bank reserves and the money supply?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Reserves decrease, money supply decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Reserves increase, money supply increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Reserves increase, money supply decreases</option>
            <option letter="d">Reserves decrease, money supply increases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During expansionary monetary policy, the Fed typically buys government securities, which increases bank reserves. These additional reserves allow banks to make more loans through the money multiplier process, leading to an increase in the money supply in the economy.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
